    {
      "role": "assistant",
      "content": "Yes, you are absolutely right; the scaling issue is actually even more critical for K-means clustering than for many other algorithms. K-means relies entirely on calculating the Euclidean distance between points to assign them to clusters, so if your features have vastly different scales, the distance metric will be dominated by the feature with the larger range, effectively rendering the other features irrelevant.\n\nIn your specific scenario, a difference of 1000 units in one feature will completely swamp the tiny differences (like 0.1) in the 0-1 feature, causing the algorithm to group data based solely on that large-scale feature rather than the true underlying patterns you want to find. To fix this, you must normalize your data before running K-means, otherwise, the resulting clusters will be meaningless and the centroids will be positioned incorrectly.\n\nThis is a classic case of a \"greedy\" algorithm where the math breaks down without proper preprocessing, so normalizing is not just a best practice here but a strict requirement for meaningful results.",
